Creating a Minecraft bot that connects to a server like `mc.h4ks.com` on port `65535` requires a significant amount of code and the use of specific libraries that are not typically supported in a web environment due to security restrictions. However, I can provide you with a simple HTML template that demonstrates how you might structure a web app for connecting to a Minecraft server using JavaScript.

Please note that this example will not actually connect to a Minecraft server, as that requires a dedicated environment and libraries like `mineflayer` or similar, which cannot be run directly in a browser. Instead, this example will show you how to set up a basic HTML structure with embedded CSS and JavaScript.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Minecraft Bot</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            color: #333;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 50px;
        }
        #connectButton {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            font-size: 16px;
            cursor: pointer;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        #status {
            margin-top: 20px;
            font-size: 18px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Minecraft Bot Connection</h1>
    <button id="connectButton">Connect to mc.h4ks.com:65535</button>
    <div id="status"></div>

    <script>
        document.getElementById('connectButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
            // This is where you would implement the connection logic
            // For demonstration purposes, we'll just simulate a connection attempt
            const statusDiv = document.getElementById('status');
            statusDiv.textContent = 'Connecting to mc.h4ks.com on port 65535...';

            // Simulate a connection attempt
            setTimeout(() => {
                // Simulate a successful connection
                statusDiv.textContent = 'Connected successfully!';
            }, 2000);
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The HTML contains a button to initiate the connection and a div to display the connection status.
- **CSS Styles**: Basic styles are applied to make the app look decent.
- **JavaScript Logic**: When the button is clicked, it simulates a connection attempt and updates the status after a delay.

### Important Note:
This code does not actually connect to a Minecraft server. To create a real Minecraft bot, you would typically use Node.js with libraries like `mineflayer`, which cannot be executed in a browser environment. If you want to create a real bot, you would need to set up a Node.js server and run the bot there.
